<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-318-248  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 318 248.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 29 1989 v6 n21 p70(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Unfilled orders for low-cost 386 PC bring mail fraud allegationsagainst Micro 1.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Micro 1 Inc. (investigations).andO;Topic:     FraudMail OrderBankruptcy.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Micro 1, a mail-order firm that offered a fully configured 20MHz 386 PC for$1,995, is reorganizing under Chapter 11 bankruptcy but still faces a federalinvestigation into mail fraud allegations.andM;The investigation began earlier this year when customers who paid in advancecomplained that they were not getting their PCs.andP;  The U.S.andP;  Postal InspectionService officials said they received more than 100 customer complaints fromlate 1988 through early 1989.andP;  Based on a preliminary investigation, federalauthorities received an injunction preventing Micro 1 from doing business.andO;On April 25, the firm filed for protection from creditors.andP;  Company officialssaid the customer problems stemmed from a contract dispute with Micro 1's PCmanufacturing supplier.andM;Micro 1 has been sold since it filed for bankruptcy, and the new owners havelanded new manufacturers, said Richard McCabe, the founder of the SanFrancisco company.andP;  PC shipments have resumed, he added.andM;Postal inspector Michael Baum, in San Francisco, expects the investigation tocontinue another eight months.andP;  If sufficient evidence is found, the companycould be indicted on felony charges, he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>